# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sequelize
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] In software engineering, the **active record pattern** is an architectural pattern.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] It is found in software that stores in-memory object data in relational databases.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] It was named by Martin Fowler in his 2003 book *Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture*.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] The interface of an object conforming to this pattern would include functions such as Insert, Update, and Delete, plus properties that correspond more or less directly to the columns in the underlying database table.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] The Active Record pattern is a Data Access Layer that performs bidirectional transfer of data between a persistent data store (often a relational database) and an in-memory data representation (the domain layer).
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] A database table or view is wrapped into a class.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] Thus, an object instance is tied to a single row in the table.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] After creation of an object, a new row is added to the table upon save.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] Any object loaded gets its information from the database.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] When an object is updated, the corresponding row in the table is also updated.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] The wrapper class implements accessor methods or properties for each column in the table or view.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] This pattern is commonly used by object persistence tools and in object–relational mapping (ORM).
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] Typically, foreign key relationships will be exposed as an object instance of the appropriate type via a property.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] Implementations of the concept can be found in various frameworks for many programming environments.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] This will find a new `Part` object based on the first matching row from the `parts` table whose `name` column has the value "gearbox".
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] Various libraries implement an active record pattern framework, such as POCO C++ Libraries in library `Poco::ActiveRecord`.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] This is a simple example of an active record object `User`, in Java.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] Here the `User` class is both the model and data access object and provides `save()`, `find()`, and `delete()` methods.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] Another critique of the active record pattern is that, due to the strong coupling of database interaction and application logic, an active record object does not follow the single responsibility principle and separation of concerns.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] This is opposed to multitier architecture, which properly addresses these practices.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] Because of this, the active record pattern is best and most often employed in simple applications that are all forms-over-data with CRUD functionality, or only as one part of an architecture.
[src:sequelize/active-record-pattern] Typically that part is data access and why several ORMs implement the active record pattern.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:sequelize/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:sequelize/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:sequelize/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:sequelize/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:sequelize/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:sequelize/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:sequelize/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:sequelize/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:sequelize/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:sequelize/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:sequelize/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:sequelize/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:sequelize/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:sequelize/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:sequelize/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:sequelize/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:sequelize/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:sequelize/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:sequelize/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:sequelize/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:sequelize/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:sequelize/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:sequelize/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:sequelize/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:sequelize/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:sequelize/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:sequelize/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:sequelize/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:sequelize/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:sequelize/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:sequelize/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:sequelize/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:sequelize/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:sequelize/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:sequelize/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:sequelize/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:sequelize/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:sequelize/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:sequelize/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:sequelize/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:sequelize/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:sequelize/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:sequelize/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:sequelize/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:sequelize/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:sequelize/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:sequelize/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:sequelize/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:sequelize/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:sequelize/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:sequelize/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:sequelize/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:sequelize/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:sequelize/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:sequelize/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:sequelize/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:sequelize/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:sequelize/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:sequelize/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:sequelize/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:sequelize/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:sequelize/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:sequelize/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:sequelize/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:sequelize/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:sequelize/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:sequelize/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:sequelize/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:sequelize/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:sequelize/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:sequelize/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:sequelize/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:sequelize/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:sequelize/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:sequelize/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:sequelize/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:sequelize/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:sequelize/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:sequelize/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:sequelize/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:sequelize/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:sequelize/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:sequelize/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:sequelize/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:sequelize/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:sequelize/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:sequelize/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:sequelize/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:sequelize/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:sequelize/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:sequelize/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:sequelize/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] In this tutorial you will learn what models are in Sequelize and how to use them.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] A model is an abstraction that represents a table in your database.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] In Sequelize, it is a class that extends Model.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] The model tells Sequelize several things about the entity it represents, such as the name of the table in the database and which columns it has (and their data types).
[src:sequelize/model-basics] This name does not have to be the same name of the table it represents in the database.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] Usually, models have singular names (such as `User`) while tables have pluralized names (such as `Users`), although this is fully configurable.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] After a model is defined, it is available within `sequelize.models` by its model name.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] To learn with an example, we will consider that we want to create a model to represent users, which have a `firstName` and a `lastName`.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] We want our model to be called `User`, and the table it represents is called `Users` in the database.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] Both ways to define this model are shown below.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] After being defined, we can access our model with `sequelize.models.User`.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] Internally, `sequelize.define` calls `Model.init`, so both approaches are essentially equivalent.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] Adding a Public Class Field with the same name as one of the model's attribute is going to cause issues.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] Sequelize adds a getter & a setter for each attribute defined through `Model.init`.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] Adding a Public Class Field will shadow those getter and setters, blocking access to the model's actual data.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] Observe that, in both methods above, the table name (`Users`) was never explicitly defined.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] However, the model name was given (`User`).
[src:sequelize/model-basics] By default, when the table name is not given, Sequelize automatically pluralizes the model name and uses that as the table name.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] This pluralization is done under the hood by a library called inflection, so that irregular plurals (such as `person -> people`) are computed correctly.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] Of course, this behavior is easily configurable.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] You can stop the auto-pluralization performed by Sequelize using the `freezeTableName: true` option.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] The example above will create a model named `User` pointing to a table also named `User`.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] This way, all tables will use the same name as the model name.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] When you define a model, you're telling Sequelize a few things about its table in the database.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] However, what if the table actually doesn't even exist in the database?
[src:sequelize/model-basics] What if it exists, but it has different columns, less columns, or any other difference?
[src:sequelize/model-basics] This is where model synchronization comes in.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] A model can be synchronized with the database by calling `model.sync(options)`, an asynchronous function (that returns a Promise).
[src:sequelize/model-basics] With this call, Sequelize will automatically perform an SQL query to the database.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] Note that this changes only the table in the database, not the model in the JavaScript side.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] You can use `sequelize.sync()` to automatically synchronize all models.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] As shown above, the `sync` and `drop` operations are destructive.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] As shown above, `sync({ force: true })` and `sync({ alter: true })` can be destructive operations.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] Therefore, they are not recommended for production-level software.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] Instead, synchronization should be done with the advanced concept of Migrations, with the help of the Sequelize CLI.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] By default, Sequelize automatically adds the fields `createdAt` and `updatedAt` to every model, using the data type `DataTypes.DATE`.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] Those fields are automatically managed as well - whenever you use Sequelize to create or update something, those fields will be set correctly.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] The `createdAt` field will contain the timestamp representing the moment of creation, and the `updatedAt` will contain the timestamp of the latest update.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] By default, Sequelize assumes that the default value of a column is `NULL`.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] Every column you define in your model must have a data type.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] Sequelize provides a lot of built-in data types.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] It becomes the `UUID` data type for PostgreSQL and SQLite, and `CHAR(36)` for MySQL.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] There are other data types, covered in a separate guide.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] When defining a column, apart from specifying the `type` of the column, and the `allowNull` and `defaultValue` options mentioned above, there are a lot more options that can be used.
[src:sequelize/model-basics] You can very easily add custom instance or class level methods.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:sequelize/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:sequelize/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:sequelize/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:sequelize/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:sequelize/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:sequelize/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:sequelize/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:sequelize/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:sequelize/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:sequelize/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:sequelize/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:sequelize/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:sequelize/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:sequelize/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:sequelize/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:sequelize/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:sequelize/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:sequelize/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:sequelize/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:sequelize/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:sequelize/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:sequelize/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:sequelize/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:sequelize/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:sequelize/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:sequelize/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:sequelize/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:sequelize/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:sequelize/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:sequelize/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:sequelize/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:sequelize/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:sequelize/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:sequelize/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:sequelize/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:sequelize/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:sequelize/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:sequelize/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:sequelize/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:sequelize/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:sequelize/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:sequelize/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:sequelize/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:sequelize/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:sequelize/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:sequelize/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
